Yet Horace avoids intruding his melancholy on his audience, as he shrinlrs from preaching, even in his most earnest moods.

The highest enthusiasms and deepest feelings were not given to Horace ; but this very fact has in no slight degree made him a place in the affections of ordinary men, who feel that he is one of them.

14. Fame—While Horace never gained among his contempo- raries the honor enjoyed by Vergil, whose imperial epic appealed to the pride, as well as the imagination‚ of the Romans, still he lived to see himself pointed out by the passers on the street as the lyric poet of Rome, a fact to which he refers in C. 4, 3, 22 f., not without a touch of pride. Augustus’ requests (cf. ἕ 9), too, show the position in which Horace stood. Many lesser poets honored him as their master and model, but their verses have all disappeared ; also the spurious works which Suetonius says were circulated under his name. His poems were early used in schools, certainly before Quintilian’s day, in Juvenal’s time, busts of Vergil and Horace adorned schoolrooms3 so that for nearly nine- teen centuries the works of Horace have formed part of liberal education in western Europe. Learned criticism and interpreta- tion by grammarians began at least as early as Nero's reign. But the best proof of Horace’s intluence in antiquity is to be seen in the numerous reminiscences, conscious and unconscious, ol his verses that are found in almost every Roman writer after him. ln the commentary of this book only a few such reminiscenees are

in later writers In fact no other Roman poet but Vergil influ- enced posterity to any like degree.
